	                <h1>
    	                <span id="Template_NewsDate1_lblDate" style="float:right">10 February 2012 10:16</span>

	                    Police thank public for info leading to arrests


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p>Lothian and Borders Police want to thank the public for
providing information that has led to a number of arrests in recent
weeks.<br />
<br />
Detective Superintendent Lesley Boal said: "We have issued a number
of appeals lately, and we are really grateful to the public for
either coming forward with information, or assisting officers as
they carry out local inquiries.<br />
<br />
"As a result, a number of crimes have been solved, and people have
appeared in court.<br />
<br />
"We rely on the public to provide us with information that can lead
to arrests, and in recent weeks this co-operation has been crucial
in leading to arrests."<br />
<br />
Among those who have been arrested and charged are:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li><span><strong>A 35-year-old man charged with the alleged
assault and robbery</strong> of a 75-year-old female in the
Groathill area on the 15th of January.</span></li>
<li><span><strong>A 16-year-old charged in connection with an
alleged indecent exposure</strong> at Drum Brae on 16 January, and
with one other similar crime</span></li>
<li><span><strong>A 22-year-old man charged with an alleged
robbery</strong> at Fauldhouse Community Development Trust on 20
January.</span></li>
<li><span><strong>A 15-year-old youth and 20-year-old male charged
with the alleged assault and robbery</strong> of a 44-year-old man
in his home, in the Groathill area on 24 January.</span></li>
<li><span><strong>A 49-year-old man charged following an alleged
indecent exposure</strong> in the Portobello area on 24 January,
and with three other similar incidents.</span></li>
<li><span><strong>Two youths charged in connection with an alleged
assault and robbery</strong> at retail premises in Haddington on 24
January.</span></li>
<li><span><strong>A 22-year-old man charged in connection with an
alleged assault and robbery</strong> on a taxi driver in the
Stenhouse area of Edinburgh on 26 January.</span></li>
<li><span><strong>A 26-year-old man charged with an alleged assault
and robbery</strong> at retail premises in Haymarket Terrace in
Edinburgh on 27 January.</span></li>
<li><span><strong>Two 22-year-old males charged in connection
with&nbsp;an alleged assault and robbery</strong>&nbsp;in a retail
premises, in the Broomhouse area on 28 January.</span></li>
<li><span><strong>Two men, aged 22 and 20, and an 18-year-old
woman, charged in connection with an alleged till snatch</strong>
in the Stenhouse area on 29 January.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><br />
<br />
Later this month, Detective Chief Inspector Gary Cunningham will be
launching an initiative tackling assaults and robberies in
Edinburgh.<br />
<br />
He said: "This type of crime has a devastating impact on the
victim, both physically and psychologically. It is a Force priority
to reduce their number and we are in the final stages of preparing
for a citywide co-ordinated initiative.<br />
<br />
"Last year there was a slight increase on the reported number of
assault and robberies in the city and we will be focusing on
reducing the number of robberies committed and will target the
callous individuals who commit them."<br />
<br />
Detective Superintendent Boal added: "The Force's Major
Investigation Team, which was introduced on 31st October, is
continuing to achieve its twin objectives of managing high risk,
high priority investigations efficiently and effectively and
returning detectives to front line policing duties where they can
focus on local serious crime. The positive results over the last
few weeks confirm that this approach is working."<br />
<br />
"While pleased with the investigative achievements over the last
week or so, we are not complacent and fully recognise that it is
important that everybody in the community feels safe."<br />
<br />
"There are a number of priority investigations still ongoing,
however we would like to highlight two such investigations which,
for obvious reasons, we need the community to assist us."</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Investigation 1<br /></strong><br />
Enquiries are ongoing to trace two persons responsible for the
robbery of a 91-year-old man who answered the door to his flat in
Duke Street on Friday (27 January) and detectives are urging anyone
who can assist with their investigation to come forward.<br />
<br />
The female suspect is described as white, around 40-years-old, 5ft
6ins tall with a thin build, weather-beaten face and long dark
hair. She was wearing dark clothing and spoke with a local
accent.<br />
<br />
The male suspect is described as white, around 40-years-old, 5ft
10ins tall with a skinny build and a clean-shaven face. He was also
wearing dark clothing and spoke with a local accent.<br />
<br />
Crimestoppers is offering a reward of up to &pound;3,000 for information
leading to an arrest and conviction of those responsible, and they
can be contacted on 0800 555 111.<br /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Investigation 2</strong></p>
<p><br />
Detectives are keen to trace a man suspected of being responsible
for assaults in Edinburgh on 28 January.<br />
<br />
The male is described as white, about 5ft 10ins tall, slim build,
dark hair, between 20 to 30 years old with a distinctive mark on
his right cheek near to his right eye, described as possibly a
mole, blemish or even a small tattoo.<br />
<br />
Superintendent Kevin Murray, from the Force's Safer Communities
Department, said: "We are conscious that in recent weeks there have
been a number of violent incidents that have taken place, all of
which have caused understandable alarm to the public.<br />
<br />
"We are of course mindful to these concerns, and we are committed
to engaging with our communities in order to address the issues
that matter most to them.<br />
<br />
"It is important to stress that crime across the Lothians and
Scottish Borders continues to fall, with 1,137 less crimes recorded
in 2011 than 2010, and 158 more detected.<br />
<br />
"Nevertheless, we recognise the impact of crimes of violence, not
only on the victims but on the public at large, and we remain
committed to bringing offenders to justice while tackling the
underlying causes of crime in order to prevent it taking
place."</p>
